data.name: label7.Text
data.value: 1.1.1. Concept of Ds: · A data structure is means of organizing data in primary memory in a form that is convenient to process by a program. · A Data Structure is created by using 2 words i.e., data and structure that means we have to store the data in the form of structure. · In C programming language there is lots of data and practically speaking different types of data, in order to manage and organize these huge number of data we need a perfect mechanism. This mechanism is termed as data structure. · Data structure allows us to effectively operate on a huge set of data for example we use array to store and manage data of similar type. An array is a simple example of data structure.

data.name: label8.Text
data.value: 1.1.2. Need of Ds: · The data structure is an important way of organizing information or data in computer. · Data Structure has a different way of storing and organizing data in computer so that it can used efficiently. · A data structure helps us to understand the relationship of one data element with other. · Data structure helps to store the data to organize the data in logical manner. · We need a way to store collections of data that may grow and shrink dynamically over time, and need to organize the information so that we can access it using efficient algorithms.

data.name: label10.Text
data.value: • The term Abstract data type(ADT) refers to basic mathematical concept that defines data types. · An ADT is a set of operation. A useful tool for specifying the logical properties of data type is the abstract data type. · ADT is defined as “ a mathematical model of the data objects that make up a data type as well as functions that operate o these objects”. · ADT is specification of logical and mathematical properties of data types or structures.

data.value: * Non-Linear Data Structure: - In Non-Linear data structure , data elements are not organized in a sequential fashion. Each elementin non-linear data structure is not constructed to have a unique predessor and a unique sucessor. -Trees and graphs are two such non-linear data structures as explained below. (i) Trees: - Tree maintain a hierarchical structure on collection of data items. - A tree is collection of one or more nodes such that there is a specially node called root and remaining nodes can be partioned into (n>=0) disjoint subjects. Each disjoint set is a tree as shown in fig 1.11.

data.value: (iii) Stack: - A Stack is a data structure in which all the insertion and deletion are performed at one end which is known as TOP of the stack - The insertion operation in stack is known as PUSH and deletion operation in stack is known as POP as shown in fig 1.9 - Stack follows LIFO (Last In First Out) mechanism. The real life examples of stacks are, plates on tray and stack of coins etc.

data.value: (ii) Linked List: - Linked List is alternative approachof arrays. If we are not aware of upper limit of number of elements in advanced then linked list one of the option. - In this organization, data can be placed anywhere in memory in memory and these data are linked with each other using pointer. This pointer field stores the address of the next element in the list. - In other words, linked list is a collection of nodes where each node consist of two parts i.e. data and pointer to next node. - The first node in the linked list is head/ start node which points to the first datat element in list and last node contains null pointer as shown in fig.

data.name: label4.Text
data.value: * Linear Data Structure: - Linear data structure is one in which its element from a sequence. It means each element in the structure has unique predecessor and a unique successor. The different type of linear data structure are given below: (i) Array: - An array is a collection of homogeneous data element. It means that an array can store one type of data only all integer, all floating point numbers or all character. - All the elements in an array are stored contiguously. The element of array are stored in lnear fashion in memory as shown in fig. 1.7

data.name: label26.Text
data.value: Space complexity is defining as the process of defining a formula for prediction of how much memory space is required for the successful execution of the algorithm. The memory space is generally considered as the primary memory.

data.name: label24.Text
data.value: The time complexity is defined as the process of determining a formula for total time required towards the execution of that algorithm. This calculation is totally independent of implementation and programming language.

data.name: label22.Text
data.value: The complexity of an algorithm computes the amount of time and spaces required by an algorithm for an input of size (n). The complexity of an algorithm can be divided into two types. The time complexity and the space complexity

data.name: label39.Text
data.value: Traverse operation is generally performed to access each and every element of data structure exactly one’s. Most of the Time, in the programs display()/ show() operation is used by programmer to display each and every element of data structure which implicitly traverse each data element of data structure.
